data.content:
Here's the idiomatic MSTest equivalent:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.AreNotEqual(0, users.Count);
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));  // no built-in predicate assert
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count());
    var admin = users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Before | After | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreNotEqual(0, x.Count)` | Clearer failure message ("expected not 0, got 0" vs "expected true, got false") |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count())` | Shows expected vs actual on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` | Purpose-built null check |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.All(...))` | *(keep as-is)* | MSTest has no `CollectionAssert.AllMatch(predicate)` |

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**

- `CollectionAssert.Contains(collection, item)` — membership check
- `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` — same elements, same order
- `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — same elements, any order
- `CollectionAssert.IsSubsetOf(subset, superset)`

> **Note:** `CollectionAssert` works on `ICollection`, so you may need `.ToList()` if your source is `IEnumerable<T>`.
